\u003E catalyses the conversion of HMG-CoA to mevalonate, which is the rate-limiting step in cholesterol biosynthesis. Statins are structural analogues of HMG-CoA and act as competitive inhibitors of this enzyme. When HMG-CoA reductase is inhibited, intracellular cholesterol levels fall, triggering increased expression of low-density lipoprotein (LDL) receptors. This leads to enhanced uptake of LDL particles from the circulation, reducing blood cholesterol levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other enzymes listed are not the primary targets of statin medications:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiolase\u003C/strong\u003E catalyses reactions in fatty acid metabolism but does not directly participate in cholesterol synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESqualene epoxydase\u003C/strong\u003E functions in a later step of cholesterol synthesis, converting squalene to lanosterol\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhosphomevalonate kinase\u003C/strong\u003E phosphorylates mevalonate-5-phosphate in the cholesterol synthesis pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsopentenyl-PP isomerase\u003C/strong\u003E catalyses the isomerisation of isopentenyl pyrophosphate in the isoprenoid pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl coenzyme A (HMG-CoA) reductase catalyses the rate-limiting step in cholesterol biosynthesis.","Statin medications competitively inhibit HMG-CoA reductase to reduce cholesterol production.","Reduced intracellular cholesterol triggers increased expression of low-density lipoprotein receptors."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: 